Price classes, and CloudFront versus S3 Cross-Region Replication.

CloudFront's per-gigabyte cost varies by edge region. Europe and North America are the cheapest; Asia-Pacific and South America are more expensive. Price classes let you opt out of the pricier regions to save money, at the cost of users in those regions being served from the next-nearest included edge, with slightly higher latency. Class All includes every edge worldwide. Class two hundred includes all except South America, Australia, and New Zealand. And Class one hundred includes North America and Europe only. Pick All for genuinely global low-latency requirements, and one hundred for cost-sensitive apps whose user base is mostly North America and Europe. Price class doesn't affect who can reach the content: a South American user can still load a Class-one-hundred distribution; they're just served from a North American edge.

CloudFront and S3 Cross-Region Replication come up together because both reduce latency for distant users, but they solve different problems. CloudFront caches objects at six-hundred-plus edges: it's read-only, T-T-L-based so it's stale until expired or invalidated, and automatically global. Cross-Region Replication copies objects to another bucket in another region: it's near real-time, fully writable, and covers only the regions you replicate to. Use CloudFront when the content is the same everywhere and you want it cached everywhere automatically. Use Replication when you need the data itself living in another region, for disaster recovery, regional read patterns, or legal residency. And they combine well: replicate to a backup region and use a CloudFront origin group to fail over to it.
